Question 1 - AR(1) with non-zero mean (10 points)

An AR(1) process with a non-zero mean \(\mu\) can be expressed by either:

\[x_t-\mu=\alpha_1(x_{t-1}-\mu)+w_t \hspace{5mm}\mbox{or}\hspace{5mm}x_t=\alpha_0+\alpha_1x_{t-1}+w_t\]

a) Define a similar relationship for an AR(2) process with mean \(\mu\)

NoteAnswer

\[ x_{t} - \mu = \alpha_{1}(x_{t-1} - \mu)+\alpha_{2}(x_{t-2}-\mu)+w_{t} \]

Question 2 - Stationarity (25 points)

a) Show that the series {\(x_t\)} given by \(x_t=\frac{3}{2}x_{t-1}-\frac{1}{2}x_{t-2}+w_t\) is non-stationary. Please use the characteristic equation method.

NoteAnswer

\[ = 1 - \frac{3}{2}\beta+\frac{1}{2}\beta^2 \]

polyroot(c(1, -3/2, 1/2)) |> abs() |> round(3)
[1] 1 2

b) Please simulate the series {\(x_t\)} using 1000 realizations and calculate the first difference {\(y_t\)}, where \(y_t=\nabla x_t\).

NoteAnswer 
set.seed(123)
n_rep <- 1000
alpha0 <- 0
alpha1 <- 1.5
alpha2 <- -0.5
sigma_sqr <- 9

dat_ts <- tibble(w = rnorm(n = n_rep, sd = sqrt(sigma_sqr))) |>
    mutate(
      index = 1:n(),
      x = 0
    ) |>
  mutate(y = w - lag(w)) |>
    tsibble::as_tsibble(index = index)

# Simulate x values
dat_ts$x[1] <- alpha0 + dat_ts$w[1]
dat_ts$x[2] <- alpha0 + alpha1 * ( dat_ts$x[1] - alpha0 ) + dat_ts$w[2]
for (i in 3:nrow(dat_ts)) {
  dat_ts$x[i] <- alpha0 + 
    alpha1 * ( dat_ts$x[i-1] - alpha0 ) + 
    alpha2 * ( dat_ts$x[i-2] - alpha0 ) + 
    dat_ts$w[i]
}

dat_ts |> 
  autoplot(.vars = x) +
    labs(
      x = "Time",
      y = "Simulated Time Series",
      title = paste("Simulated Values from an AR(2) Process with Mean", alpha0)
    ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(
      plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)
    ) 
dat_ts |> 
  autoplot(.vars = y) +
    labs(
      x = "Time",
      y = "Simulated Time Series",
      title = paste("Simulated Values from the first difference of an AR(2) Process with Mean", alpha0)
    ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(
      plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)
    )

c) Prove that \(y_t\) is stationary, use the characteristic equation method.

NoteAnswer

\[ 1 - \frac{1}{2}B + \frac{1}{2}B^2 = 0 \]

polyroot(c(1, -1/2, .5)) |> abs() |> round(3)
[1] 1.414 1.414

The polyroot returns values greater than 1 and so the it is stationary.

Question 3 - Partial Correlogram (40 points)

a) Please use the Holt-Winters method to decompose the US Industrial Production Index. Please justify your choice of parameters. Use the context and your understanding of the series as part of your answers.

NoteAnswer 
ind_ts <- ind_prod %>% 
  mutate(
    yearmonth = yearmonth(date)
  ) %>% 
  select(yearmonth, ind_prod_indx) %>% 
  tsibble(index = yearmonth)

ind_HW <- ind_ts %>% 
  model(Additive = ETS(ind_prod_indx ~ trend("M", alpha = 0.5, beta = 0.001) + error("M") + season("M", gamma = 0.01),
                       opt_crit = "amse", nmse = 1))

ind_HW %>% 
  augment() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = yearmonth)) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = ind_prod_indx, colour = "Actual Data"), linewidth = 0.7) +
  geom_line(aes(y = .fitted, colour = "Fitted (Holt Winters)"), linewidth = 0.7) +
  scale_colour_manual(values = c("Actual Data" = "black",
                                 "Fitted (Holt Winters)" = "red")) +
  labs(
    title = "Holt Winters Model: US Industrial Production Index",
    x = "Date",
    y = "Industrial Production Index",
    color = "Series"
  ) +
  theme_bw()

The smoothing parameters used were \(\alpha:\) 0.5, \(\beta:\) 0.001, and \(\gamma:\) 0.01. A multiplicative model was used as the degree in variation increases with the trend. The high alpha value is used due to the large fluctuations in the data are better matched with it. The beta and gamma are much smaller as the seasonality and long-term trend are consistent.

b) Plot the remainder (random) component of the decomposed series.

NoteAnswer 
ind_res <- augment(ind_HW) %>% 
  pull(.resid)

acf(na.omit(ind_res), plot=TRUE, type="correlation",
    main="Holt Winters Random Component")

c) Plot a partial correlogram of the random component of the the US Industrial Production Index. What kind of autoregressive process would you pick to model the random component?

NoteAnswer 
pacf(ind_res, plot=TRUE)

The lag 1 and 2 are significant suggesting an AR(2) model could be a good fit. The significant lags show the current value is influenced by the last two values. Past the second lag there are significant lags but these may not practically significant. I would use an AR(2) model as it appears to capture the residual effect without overfitting.
